# Prologue: Moment of Resolve

The monsters quivered in fear, realising that all their hopes were placed on Rimuru. The reports they recieved were enough to send chills down the spines of every executive in the nation of Tempest.

Benimaru awoke in a bed in the labyrinth’s recreation facility infirmary, where Souei had carried him. Not much time had passed since the battle at the Sacred Tree. A crushing sense of loss jolted him upright. Gabiru and Geld, resting nearby, woke at the same moment, as if drawn by the same instinct.

Soon after, the executives gathered in the Control Room within the labyrinth. Eight of the Twelve Guardians were present: Diablo, Zegion, and Kumara, who had remained behind to defend the labyrinth. Benimaru, Gabil, and Geld. Ranga, recovering within Gobta’s shadow.
Testarossa, who had rushed back urgently from the Kingdom of Engrassia. Her decision to abandon her post and entrust matters to her subordinates spoke volumes about the severity of the situation. Alongside them were Shuna, Rigurd, Gobta, Apito, and others responsible for governance. Everyone who could move had assembled.

Ramiris, now overseeing the Control Room, gasped as the report was delivered. The labyrinth was under attack, but that was not the real issue. The true shock lay elsewhere. Ramiris stood frozen in disbelief. Beretta and Treyni were visibly shaken, though silent. Charys, who had seen Veldora off earlier, struggled to remain composed.

It was Souei who spoke. Through his clones, he had been monitoring events more closely than anyone. And now, he delivered the news: Rimuru has disappeared.

“Is it true… that Rimuru-sama has disappeared?” 

Benimaru asked on behalf of everyone. Yet even as he spoke, he did not doubt Souei. If anything, it was the opposite. He could no longer feel the connection to Rimuru within himself—that was why he wanted Souei to deny it.

“…Yes. I’m certain. I couldn’t even remain by his side as an escort…”

Souei’s voice was heavy with regret. No one blamed him. From what he described, the outcome would not have changed—no matter who had been there. Rimuru himself, the one they all trusted, had been taken. Now was not the time for blame.

Silence filled the Control Room.

Then, With a deafening crash, a desk shattered.

“…And this happened while I was there.”

Souei, normally composed beyond measure, had lost control.  Even Testarossa closed her eyes in silent agreement.
 
 *…I couldn’t do anything either.*

 Guilt weighed heavily on her. She had sent Rimuru—someone she deeply respected—into that battle. She had no right to console Souei. She could only confront her own helplessness. That sentiment was shared by everyone present.

![break]

“Don’t be so arrogant, Souei. All you would have done, it would have only added another meaningless death.”

Diablo's cold, calculating voice cut through the silence. His words were harsh—but not wrong. Souei understood that, and said nothing. He lacked even the energy to argue. He could only endure the weight of his failure. Diablo sighed.

“You’ve gone too far.”

Testarossa spoke calmly, exhaling before continuing.

“No one here could have changed the outcome against Milim-sama. Not even you, Diablo.”

Her gaze was sharp. She understood what Diablo was doing. He was provoking them—stirring anger to counter despair.  If they gave in to grief, they would collapse. They needed something stronger. Anger was the quickest fuel. Diablo knew that. And so did Testarossa. That was precisely why she could not allow it.

"Trying to cast yourself as the villain so that you'd get thrown out to be able to challenge Feldway by yourself right...? Diablo??”

“Tsks...”

*This is exactly why I can’t stand this woman*, Diablo thought bitterly. He had known her too long to hide anything from her. Though he appeared composed, he was barely holding himself together.

*Why didn’t you take me with you, Rimuru-sama…?*

Testarossa saw through that too, and spoke on, without mercy.

“I hear you disgraced yourself in front of Rimuru-sama.”

“What?”

“You were frozen in time and couldn’t act, correct? How disappointing.”

"Keh-heh-heh-heh..."

Diablo’s smile twisted.

"And yet, you let a weak enemy escape, did you not, Testarossa?”

Diablo's eyes pierced into directly into Testarossa with naked hostility. 

No one spoke, The tension in the control room spiking, and despair hung heavy in the air. Geld and Gabiru remained silent, Kumara trembled, Benimaru clenched his fists, and Ramiris lay face down, on the verge of tears. Rimuru had always been there.

Now, he was gone.

It was almost fortunate that Shion, the most hot-tempered among them, was absent. Had she been present, her impulsiveness might have driven them all toward ruin.

But that was only a possibility.

There was still one person who did not waver.

Zegion stood.

Uncrossing his arms, he rose and spoke with quiet authority.


“Nonsense. What are you all so afraid of? What does it matter that Rimuru-sama has disappeared?”

He remained utterly composed, as though questioning everyone’s panic.

“If Rimuru-sama is truly our lord, he will return—even from beyond time and space. If not, then there is a reason.”

His conviction was absolute.

A spark of hope ignited within them.

“Have you all forgotten? We are not children abandoned by a parent. Think. Feel it. Rimuru-sama’s blessing is still with us.”

His words rang true. Though the connection to Rimuru felt severed, something remained—a faint warmth, an unseen presence. Whether it was merely a lingering trace or something more, none could say.

Many had noticed it, yet dismissed it as wishful thinking. Better not to hope than to be crushed by false expectations.

But they had been wrong.

Only those who refuse to give up can carve a path forward.

Benimaru nodded slowly. “You’re right.”

Memories surfaced—of past failures, of the chaos he caused when that connection had once been lost. He had sworn never to repeat that mistake.

And yet, here he was again.

Now, with Rimuru gone, the responsibility fell to him.

Benimaru let out a quiet breath and smiled wryly. “Then we prove it. That we can handle things ourselves—so he won’t worry when he returns.”

“That’s right!” Gobta said brightly. “Rimuru-sama’s not dead! He’ll come back no matter what!”

Rigurd struck him lightly. “Idiot. Watch your mouth.”

Still, he nodded. “We’ve relied on him too much. Now we act—for his sake.”

The others agreed. The atmosphere shifted, despair giving way to resolve.

“There’s no point in lamenting anymore,” Gabiru said. “Rimuru-sama would only laugh at us for it.”

“Souei-dono’s report is troubling,” Geld added gravely, “but it is impossible for Rimuru-sama to be defeated. There must be a reason.”

“That’s right!” Ramiris said, regaining her energy. “I wasn’t worried at all!”

The others nodded, Kumara adding, “Rimuru-sama can’t lose!”

Hope spread, filling the room.

Benimaru watched them and realized something.

I wasn’t the only one relying on him.

Rimuru’s mere presence had brought them all comfort. But that reliance had also meant placing everything on his shoulders.

“That kind of reliance,” Benimaru said quietly, “is just shifting responsibility.”

His casual remark carried weight. Faces tightened in understanding.

“I’ve left everything to him for too long,” he continued. “This is our chance. Let’s overcome this with our own strength.”

Rigurd nodded firmly. “Yes. Let’s ensure we can welcome Rimuru-sama back with smiles.”

Souei stepped forward. “Zegion… my apologies. I lost my composure.”

But his eyes were steady now, his resolve clear.

One by one, the others voiced their determination.

Diablo chuckled softly. “Kufufufu… It seems my encouragement wasn’t necessary.”

“You went too far,” Zegion replied.

“Perhaps. But if they couldn’t recover from that, they’d be unworthy of Rimuru-sama.”

On the large screen, the invading forces advanced through the labyrinth. There was no more time for internal conflict. Still, this moment had been necessary—had they failed to regain themselves, defeat would have been inevitable.

Now, that concern was gone.

“You’re right, Zegion,” Diablo said. “We must prove we can stand on our own. First, we eliminate these invaders. Then we rescue Carrera and the others trapped in the ice.”

Testarossa smiled faintly. “Agreed. If Veldora-sama has gone to Ultima, we need not worry. I will assist Carrera.”

Diablo nodded. “We must also rescue Milim-sama’s subordinates. I’m counting on you.”

Without hesitation, Testarossa departed.

Benimaru turned to Diablo. “And you?”

Diablo glanced at the screen and smiled wryly. “I intended to eliminate Feldway and present this world to Rimuru-sama… but I’ve reconsidered. Strengthening our defenses may better align with his wishes.”

His tone was light, but the implication was serious.

Zegion reacted immediately. Benimaru frowned. “You think they’re that dangerous?”

The enemy data filled the screen: Vega, Dino, Pico, Gracia, and Mai Furuki—the so-called Seven Angels of Death. Each possessed immense power, easily exceeding a million, some surpassing ten million.

They were certainly threats—but not enough to trouble Diablo, or so it seemed.

“Just in case,” Diablo said. “It’s not that I doubt Zegion.”

Zegion shook his head. “No need. I will do my duty.”

His resolve to protect the labyrinth was absolute.

“If that’s settled, I’ll go.”

Without hesitation, Zegion turned and left, Apito following with a respectful bow.

With the labyrinth’s strongest guardian in place, there was nothing to fear.

Ramiris relaxed visibly. “With Zegion here, we’re safe.”

Beretta and Treyni silently agreed.

“I will focus on recovery,” Geld said, closing his eyes. Though restless, he understood his role.

“I must rest as well,” Gabiru added. His wounds had healed, but his body and magicule reserves had not yet recovered. He worried about Eurazania, now frozen, about Carrera and the others—and about Suphia.

If I were alone, I would run there immediately…

But he had responsibilities.

He forced those thoughts down and committed himself to recovery.

Thus, Tempest’s executives began to move. Their anxiety had vanished, replaced by determination.

They were no longer helpless without Rimuru.

They understood their roles.

And they would fulfill them.

They would not disgrace the name of Demon Lord Rimuru.

And when he returned—

They would stand before him, worthy of his praise.

Now is the time for them to leave the protection of Rimuru, the one who gave them their names.  

